pullRequest.body:
This file proves Mason-Stothers theorem (i.e. polynomial ABC). For coprime polynomials $a, b, c$ over a field (of arbitrary characteristic) with $a + b + c = 0$, we have $\max\{\deg(a), \deg(b), \deg(c)\} + 1 \le \deg(\mathrm{rad}(abc))$ or $a' = b' = c' = 0$.

---

I pushed a small modification to another file. The lines

can now be removed, adding `[DecidableEq k]`. I suggest a slightly modified proof of the main result:
```lean
/-- **Polynomial ABC theorem.** -/
theorem Polynomial.abc {a b c : k[X]} (ha : a ‚â† 0) (hb : b ‚â† 0) (hc : c ‚â† 0) (hab : IsCoprime a b)
    (hbc : IsCoprime b c) (hca : IsCoprime c a) (hsum : a + b + c = 0) :
    ( natDegree a + 1 ‚â§ (radical (a * b * c)).natDegree ‚àß
      natDegree b + 1 ‚â§ (radical (a * b * c)).natDegree ‚àß
      natDegree c + 1 ‚â§ (radical (a * b * c)).natDegree ) ‚à®
      derivative a = 0 ‚àß derivative b = 0 ‚àß derivative c = 0 := by
  -- Utility assertions
  have wbc := wronskian_eq_of_sum_zero hsum
  set w := wronskian a b with wab
  have wca : w = wronskian c a := by
    rw [add_rotate] at hsum
    simpa only [‚Üê wbc] using wronskian_eq_of_sum_zero hsum
  have abc_dr_dvd_w : divRadical (a * b * c) ‚à£ w := by
    have adr_dvd_w := divRadical_dvd_wronskian_left a b
    have bdr_dvd_w := divRadical_dvd_wronskian_right a b
    have cdr_dvd_w := divRadical_dvd_wronskian_right b c
    rw [‚Üê wab] at adr_dvd_w bdr_dvd_w
    rw [‚Üê wbc] at cdr_dvd_w
    rw [divRadical_mul (hca.symm.mul_left hbc), divRadical_mul hab]
    exact (hca.divRadical.symm.mul_left hbc.divRadical).mul_dvd
      (hab.divRadical.mul_dvd adr_dvd_w bdr_dvd_w) cdr_dvd_w
  by_cases hw : w = 0
  ¬∑ right
    rw [hw] at wab wbc
    cases' hab.wronskian_eq_zero_iff.mp wab.symm with ga gb
    cases' hbc.wronskian_eq_zero_iff.mp wbc.symm with _ gc
    exact ‚ü®ga, gb, gc‚ü©
  ¬∑ left
    refine ‚ü®?_, ?_, ?_‚ü©
    ¬∑ rw [mul_rotate] at abc_dr_dvd_w ‚ä¢
      apply abc_subcall wbc <;> assumption
    ¬∑ rw [‚Üê mul_rotate] at abc_dr_dvd_w ‚ä¢
      apply abc_subcall wca <;> assumption
    ¬∑ apply abc_subcall wab <;> assumption
```

Do we want this auxiliary function for maximum of three natural numbers in the statement of Mason--Stothers? I wonder how other parts of mathlib represent maximum values of three numbers.

We usually just write `max (max a b) c`, or `a ‚äî b ‚äî c` if you prefer infixes. But also you are using it to state `max (max a b) c ‚â§ d`, in which situation we much prefer writing `a ‚â§ d ‚àß b ‚â§ d ‚àß c ‚â§ d`
Should we remove all `max‚ÇÉ` related apis and work with `max`-related things then?

and everywhere else

I'll put under `Mathlib.RingTheory.Polynomial` then (IMO these theorems are to specific so I'm not sure if it worths to make new files for it).

I just realized that first half of the theorems & definition of `divRadical` actually makes sense for `EuclideanDomain` as well, but not sure if I put these under the "euclidean domain" files. Do you have any suggestions? I think another way is to put `divRadical`-related theorems, up to `divRadical_dvd_self`, in `Mathlib.RingTheory.Radical` with `EuclideanDomain` version, and put the rest in `Mathlib.RingTheory.Polynomial`? (Honestly I've never seen any mathematical proofs using $x / \mathrm{rad}(x)$ except for Mason-Stothers...)

(these two are not included in #18452 for now)
